 are both dependent on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 .
 This means that every age would correspond to a different coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\tau+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 affects only the consumer age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 this would mean that only consumers aged 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau,\tau+1$
\end_inset

 can be used for estimation.
 An assumption on how 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\tau+1}$
\end_inset

 may depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 may be a better approach for data.
 To answer what this dependence should look like, consider how the utility
 for the same level of quality and assets would change over age.
 We would expect more utility through quality in the early years and less
 during the middle-ages - followed by a mild increase in preference for
 quality in the later years.
 A general fitting function (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{a}e^{-x^{b}}$
\end_inset

) can be provided but we should provide both a simple-form and one that
 adds up to the past utilities.
 A common function is the discounting function 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{(1+\delta)^{\tau}}$
\end_inset

 .
 We believe that this relation should depend on needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 - which itself is attached with life-cycle - the effect of age is aligned
 with the trajectory of needs.
 One simple option is to keep the form 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-\frac{(x-30)^{2}}{a}}$
\end_inset

.
 We could estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a_{\tau}}{b_{\tau}}$
\end_inset

 - but to accommodate the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

-dependent factors, we need to have an explicit dependence 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\tau}$
\end_inset

) on 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 - arguing that individuals with different 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 would have a different behaviour.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to see the effect of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is to consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\rho}\nu_{\tau+1}$
\end_inset

 in the optimisation so that first-order conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau+1}=a_{\tau+1}ln(\nu_{\tau+1})+b_{\tau+1}ln(A_{\tau+1})+(1-a_{\tau+1}-b_{\tau+1})ln(\sum_{\rho}\nu_{\tau+1})$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a_{\tau+1}}{\nu_{\tau+1}}-\frac{b_{\tau+1}}{A_{\tau+1}}+\frac{(1-a_{\tau+1}-b_{\tau+1})}{G(\rho,\tau+1)}$
\end_inset

=0 where 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\rho,\tau+1)=\sum_{\rho}\nu_{\tau+1}$
\end_inset

.
 This would lead to a quadratic formulation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\tau+1}$
\end_inset

.
 If we continue assuming that consumer choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\tau+1}$
\end_inset

 has no influence on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\rho}\nu_{\tau+1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

